11
00:00:22,690 --> 00:00:24,600
So one of your areas of expertise

12
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:27,360
is the United Front work in Hong Kong.

13
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:28,720
What is the United Front?

14
00:00:28,720 --> 00:00:32,349
The United Front was originally the strategy

15
00:00:32,349 --> 00:00:36,160
of the Chinese Communist Party to cooperate

16
00:00:36,160 --> 00:00:38,979
with the Nationalist Party in China

17
00:00:38,979 --> 00:00:43,899
during the early 1920s and later during the
1930s

18
00:00:43,899 --> 00:00:46,089
to fight against the Japanese

19
00:00:46,089 --> 00:00:50,199
so that both sides can form a kind of alliance

20
00:00:50,199 --> 00:00:52,699
to deal with the Second World War.

21
00:00:52,699 --> 00:00:56,839
The United Front work later on has evolved
into

22
00:00:56,839 --> 00:01:00,850
an instrument used by the Chinese Communist
Party

23
00:01:00,850 --> 00:01:03,940
to win the hearts and minds of the people.

24
00:01:03,940 --> 00:01:06,470
And in the context of Hong Kong,

25
00:01:06,470 --> 00:01:09,990
United Front means that the Chinese government

26
00:01:09,990 --> 00:01:12,500
has to do everything in order to win

27
00:01:12,500 --> 00:01:14,980
the hearts and minds of the Hong Kong people.

28
00:01:14,980 --> 00:01:16,740
So what are some of the goals of the United
Front?

29
00:01:16,740 --> 00:01:19,110
Who are they targeting in Hong Kong?

30
00:01:19,110 --> 00:01:22,840
The goals of United Front is to number one,

31
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:26,450
to win the political support of the ordinary
people

32
00:01:26,450 --> 00:01:30,080
and secondly to get the support of the Hong
Kong people

33
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:34,350
who would support not only the local government
of Hong Kong,

34
00:01:34,350 --> 00:01:37,220
but also the central government in Beijing.

35
00:01:37,220 --> 00:01:41,780
And thirdly, United Front work aims to prevent

36
00:01:41,780 --> 00:01:47,450
the local Democrats from grabbing more seats
in the legislature

37
00:01:47,450 --> 00:01:51,340
and also the district councils because in
the minds of Beijing,

38
00:01:51,340 --> 00:01:54,170
if the political opposition in Hong Kong

39
00:01:54,170 --> 00:01:56,670
can get into political power,

40
00:01:56,670 --> 00:01:59,679
then the situation in Hong Kong would be tipped

41
00:01:59,679 --> 00:02:02,710
in favor of the opposition rather than Beijing.

42
00:02:02,710 --> 00:02:06,579
So basically the goal is to make Hong Kong
less autonomous

43
00:02:06,579 --> 00:02:10,450
and more in line with the Communist Party's
goals.

44
00:02:10,450 --> 00:02:13,430
In the minds of Beijing, United Front work

45
00:02:13,430 --> 00:02:17,650
can coexist with the autonomy of Hong Kong.

46
00:02:17,650 --> 00:02:19,020
Because in the minds of Beijing,

47
00:02:19,020 --> 00:02:21,980
if United Front work is successful,

48
00:02:21,980 --> 00:02:26,480
then the pro-Beijing forces would garner sufficient
public support

49
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:29,840
and capture most of the seats in the legislature.

50
00:02:29,840 --> 00:02:30,840


51
00:02:30,840 --> 00:02:33,650
So how does the United Front infiltrate a
Hong Kong society?

52
00:02:33,650 --> 00:02:37,420
The United Front work infiltrates into Hong
Kong society

53
00:02:37,420 --> 00:02:41,800
by using many interest groups like women,

54
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:46,590
like labor unions or like district [inaudible]

55
00:02:46,590 --> 00:02:49,640
or even like neighborhood associations.

56
00:02:49,640 --> 00:02:51,290
Many of these interest groups were formerly

57
00:02:51,290 --> 00:02:54,140
pro-British before 1997

58
00:02:54,140 --> 00:02:57,790
but after 1997 most of these interest groups

59
00:02:57,790 --> 00:03:01,750
have turned to Beijing mainly because of political
loyalty

60
00:03:01,750 --> 00:03:04,780
and also because of financial incentives.

61
00:03:04,780 --> 00:03:07,200
Because Beijing has dished out a lot of

62
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:09,760
financial and monetary incentives

63
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,150
to all these leaders of the interest groups.

64
00:03:13,150 --> 00:03:14,150
And most importantly,

65
00:03:14,150 --> 00:03:15,780
the leaders of the interest groups

66
00:03:15,780 --> 00:03:18,050
have been appointed to the Chinese People's

67
00:03:18,050 --> 00:03:20,250
Political Consultative Conference,

68
00:03:20,250 --> 00:03:23,040
the Chinese National People's Congress.

69
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:26,210
So in terms of status, inference and power,

70
00:03:26,210 --> 00:03:28,990
those co-opted Hong Kong elites,

71
00:03:28,990 --> 00:03:33,300
they feel that they are more politically powerful
than ever before.

72
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:34,750
Is it just special interest groups

73
00:03:34,750 --> 00:03:40,100
or is the United Front involved in the education?

74
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:41,100
Business sector?

75
00:03:41,100 --> 00:03:45,660
The United Front work also involves deeply
in the business sector

76
00:03:45,660 --> 00:03:48,710
because many business people are highly pragmatic.

77
00:03:48,710 --> 00:03:50,950
They want to do business with China,

78
00:03:50,950 --> 00:03:53,290
they don't want to antagonize China.

79
00:03:53,290 --> 00:03:56,540
So the business sector is particularly vulnerable.

80
00:03:56,540 --> 00:03:59,530
The least vulnerable sector in Hong Kong

81
00:03:59,530 --> 00:04:01,440
or to put it in another way,

82
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:04,870
the most resistant sector to United Front
work

83
00:04:04,870 --> 00:04:06,540
is the education.

84
00:04:06,540 --> 00:04:08,350
Because in the education sectors,

85
00:04:08,350 --> 00:04:12,460
many intellectuals, academics, students,

86
00:04:12,460 --> 00:04:16,239
they are highly post materialistic if you
like.

87
00:04:16,239 --> 00:04:17,239
In other words,

88
00:04:17,239 --> 00:04:20,440
they attach importance to values like human
rights,

89
00:04:20,440 --> 00:04:23,940
democracy, sustainable development, civil
liberties,

90
00:04:23,940 --> 00:04:27,610
and they are less interested in material incentives.

91
00:04:27,610 --> 00:04:28,750
So from this perspective,

92
00:04:28,750 --> 00:04:35,200
the education sector is the least vulnerable
to United Front work.

93
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:37,750
I'm curious, you talked about the business
sector.

94
00:04:37,750 --> 00:04:40,180
How can you tell the difference between United
Front work

95
00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:42,700
and just organic natural exchanges

96
00:04:42,700 --> 00:04:45,040
between mainland China and Hong Kong?

97
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:50,280
The organic exchanges between mainland China
and Hong Kong

98
00:04:50,280 --> 00:04:54,060
involves some more formalistic levels of exchange,

99
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:55,550
like for example, you know,

100
00:04:55,550 --> 00:04:58,340
business associations interacting with

101
00:04:58,340 --> 00:04:59,820
the Chinese government departments.

102
00:04:59,820 --> 00:05:02,270
Before United Front work,

103
00:05:02,270 --> 00:05:07,980
it can proceed from formal to more informal
co-optation.

104
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:10,460
That is to say they try to make friends with
you

105
00:05:10,460 --> 00:05:13,680
and in the process of making friends,

106
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:18,430
they try to woo your side to support their
side politically.

107
00:05:18,430 --> 00:05:23,270
So gradually the co-opted targets become their
friends,

108
00:05:23,270 --> 00:05:25,520
and even solid supporters.

109
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:30,350
So it is a kind of a longterm movement to
win friendship,

110
00:05:30,350 --> 00:05:34,460
to change friendship to political loyalty.

111
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:36,120
And when we're talking about the United Front,

112
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:38,720
the United Front is actually a division of

113
00:05:38,720 --> 00:05:41,830
the Chinese Communist Party itself, correct?

114
00:05:41,830 --> 00:05:44,910
The United Front Department within the Chinese
Communist Party

115
00:05:44,910 --> 00:05:48,480
is mainly responsible for United Front work.

116
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:51,190
However many other Chinese departments

117
00:05:51,190 --> 00:05:53,560
are also dealing with United Front work.

118
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:55,970
For example, in the case of Hong Kong

119
00:05:55,970 --> 00:05:57,460
we have their liaison office,

120
00:05:57,460 --> 00:05:59,090
which is the representative office

121
00:05:59,090 --> 00:06:02,380
of the Central Government in Hong Kong

122
00:06:02,380 --> 00:06:05,670
and it is also responsible for United Front
work.

123
00:06:05,670 --> 00:06:10,100
And quite often when the mainland Chinese
government departments

124
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:11,889
come to visit Hong Kong,

125
00:06:11,889 --> 00:06:13,570
they may interact with some of

126
00:06:13,570 --> 00:06:15,930
the business associations in Hong Kong.

127
00:06:15,930 --> 00:06:20,360
And quite often United Front work is defined
broadly.

128
00:06:20,360 --> 00:06:22,550
That is to say to win friendship,

129
00:06:22,550 --> 00:06:25,480
to interact with our potential friends

130
00:06:25,480 --> 00:06:27,100
and then to gain their political

131
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:29,410
and economic support in the long run.

132
00:06:29,410 --> 00:06:32,020
So United Front work in China

133
00:06:32,020 --> 00:06:35,400
is not conducted solely by the United Front
department.

134
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:39,150
It can be conducted by many other departments
as well.

135
00:06:39,150 --> 00:06:42,030
So sort of like a whole of society method

136
00:06:42,030 --> 00:06:44,450
of subverting and changing a society

137
00:06:44,450 --> 00:06:46,880
to be in line with the Communist Party of
China?

138
00:06:46,880 --> 00:06:50,380
Yeah, we can describe it as a kind of mechanism

139
00:06:50,380 --> 00:06:52,770
in which various Chinese departments

140
00:06:52,770 --> 00:06:56,510
are engaging with their opposite numbers,

141
00:06:56,510 --> 00:07:01,260
so as to win the hearts and minds of the targeted
people,

142
00:07:01,260 --> 00:07:04,350
targeted interest groups and targeted organizations.

143
00:07:04,350 --> 00:07:07,430
So how successful has United Front work been
in Hong Kong?

144
00:07:07,430 --> 00:07:09,070
Actually, United Front work

145
00:07:09,070 --> 00:07:11,550
has been quite successful in Hong Kong,

146
00:07:11,550 --> 00:07:14,220
particularly since the 2012

147
00:07:14,220 --> 00:07:17,010
when the anti national education campaign

148
00:07:17,010 --> 00:07:19,949
was launched by many young parents

149
00:07:19,949 --> 00:07:22,690
and also students as well as intellectuals.

150
00:07:22,690 --> 00:07:26,710
However, the October the,

151
00:07:26,710 --> 00:07:34,400
the September to December Occupy Central movement
in 2014

152
00:07:34,400 --> 00:07:39,280
constituted a strong resistance to United
Front work in China.

153
00:07:39,280 --> 00:07:42,930
Many young people in Hong Kong together with
intellectuals,

154
00:07:42,930 --> 00:07:46,080
they were determined to push for democratization

155
00:07:46,080 --> 00:07:50,190
by using the Occupy Central movement, in 2014.

156
00:07:50,190 --> 00:07:55,400
It failed, and so United Front work in China
has deepened further,

157
00:07:55,400 --> 00:08:02,440
until this year when the government of Hong
Kong led by Carrie Lam

158
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:05,790
decided to introduce an extradition bill

159
00:08:05,790 --> 00:08:10,310
and that extradition bill alienated many young
Hong Kong people

160
00:08:10,310 --> 00:08:12,940
as well as ordinary people,

161
00:08:12,940 --> 00:08:16,620
because many people were frightened that such
extradition bill

162
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:19,020
would probably lead to the possibility

163
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:22,120
that many Hong Kong people would be transfer

164
00:08:22,120 --> 00:08:24,270
from Hong Kong to mainland China.

165
00:08:24,270 --> 00:08:27,270
So United Front work that has its limitations.

166
00:08:27,270 --> 00:08:30,550
The limitation is that with the education
sector

167
00:08:30,550 --> 00:08:33,529
being very resistant to United Front work,

168
00:08:33,529 --> 00:08:35,959
the extradition bill has failed to win

169
00:08:35,959 --> 00:08:38,430
the hearts and minds of the ordinary people.

170
00:08:38,430 --> 00:08:40,050
So what is it about the education sector

171
00:08:40,050 --> 00:08:44,279
that makes United Front work not work?

172
00:08:44,279 --> 00:08:46,420
The education sector is characterized

173
00:08:46,420 --> 00:08:50,079
by very independent minded intellectuals

174
00:08:50,079 --> 00:08:53,220
whose understanding of China

175
00:08:53,220 --> 00:08:57,339
is not really through ideological indoctrination

176
00:08:57,339 --> 00:08:58,959
or even socialization.

177
00:08:58,959 --> 00:09:02,579
Unlike the mainland Chinese intellectuals
and students

178
00:09:02,579 --> 00:09:04,269
who were educated in the mainland,

179
00:09:04,269 --> 00:09:08,069
who are socialized and indoctrinated to combine

180
00:09:08,069 --> 00:09:11,230
the cultural identity with the political identity

181
00:09:11,230 --> 00:09:14,889
of accepting the CCP rule in the mainland.

182
00:09:14,889 --> 00:09:18,249
In Hong Kong, traditionally the colonial rulers

183
00:09:18,249 --> 00:09:21,999
were very loose in educating Hong Kong people

184
00:09:21,999 --> 00:09:24,459
not to mention about Chinese nationalism.

185
00:09:24,459 --> 00:09:27,809
So in Hong Kong traditionally and historically

186
00:09:27,809 --> 00:09:33,379
the education system did not inculcate strong
patriotic sentiment

187
00:09:33,379 --> 00:09:35,899
in the psyche of many young people.

188
00:09:35,899 --> 00:09:42,610
And after 1997 this perhaps semi-colonial
education legacy persists.

189
00:09:42,610 --> 00:09:45,990
Not only that, with the era of globalization,

190
00:09:45,990 --> 00:09:48,980
many young Hong Kong people understand China

191
00:09:48,980 --> 00:09:52,050
not through the textbook but through the Internet.

192
00:09:52,050 --> 00:09:54,689
So in that sense the education sector in Hong
Kong

193
00:09:54,689 --> 00:09:56,730
is highly autonomous.

194
00:09:56,730 --> 00:09:58,790
So how does the United Front respond to things

195
00:09:58,790 --> 00:10:02,300
like the Umbrella Movement or the extradition
bill protests,

196
00:10:02,300 --> 00:10:04,319
much of which is student led,

197
00:10:04,319 --> 00:10:05,779
student and teacher led?

198
00:10:05,779 --> 00:10:08,240
The United Front, you know,

199
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:13,360
machinery responds to the Umbrella Movement

200
00:10:13,360 --> 00:10:19,990
by resuscitating or reorganizing the youth
groups in Hong Kong.

201
00:10:19,990 --> 00:10:23,829
They try to organize many pro-Beijing youth
groups

202
00:10:23,829 --> 00:10:27,600
to support mainland's policy towards Hong
Kong

203
00:10:27,600 --> 00:10:31,429
such as the recent Greater Bay Area plan

204
00:10:31,429 --> 00:10:33,620
in which young people of Hong Kong

205
00:10:33,620 --> 00:10:36,610
are encouraged to do business in China,

206
00:10:36,610 --> 00:10:40,040
to work in China and even to reside in China.

207
00:10:40,040 --> 00:10:43,459
However, the opposition to the extradition
bill

208
00:10:43,459 --> 00:10:48,720
has dealt a severe blow to China's United
Front work in Hong Kong

209
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:52,639
because many young people are proven to be
very resistant

210
00:10:52,639 --> 00:10:56,529
to the idea of political and economic integration

211
00:10:56,529 --> 00:10:59,399
between Hong Kong and mainland China.

212
00:10:59,399 --> 00:11:01,470
And I know the United Front is very active

213
00:11:01,470 --> 00:11:03,410
in countries around the world.

214
00:11:03,410 --> 00:11:05,620
How does the United Front work in Hong Kong

215
00:11:05,620 --> 00:11:08,029
tie into United Front work globally?

216
00:11:08,029 --> 00:11:10,999
United Front work in Hong Kong cannot be easily

217
00:11:10,999 --> 00:11:15,170
translated into foreign countries for several
reasons.

218
00:11:15,170 --> 00:11:17,639
Number one, in other foreign countries,

219
00:11:17,639 --> 00:11:22,970
there are many overseas Chinese who have long
been assimilated

220
00:11:22,970 --> 00:11:26,410
into the mainstream society of these countries.

221
00:11:26,410 --> 00:11:30,350
So they are not so vulnerable to United Front
work.

222
00:11:30,350 --> 00:11:33,860
Secondly, United Front work conducted by China

223
00:11:33,860 --> 00:11:36,940
tends to focus on the individuals,

224
00:11:36,940 --> 00:11:40,300
like the individuals, politicians or the individuals

225
00:11:40,300 --> 00:11:43,920
who tend to have a emotional attachment to
China.

226
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:45,899
So in other words,

227
00:11:45,899 --> 00:11:48,779
United Front work in Hong Kong is one thing.

228
00:11:48,779 --> 00:11:50,680
United Front work, you know,

229
00:11:50,680 --> 00:11:53,720
conducted by China in foreign countries

230
00:11:53,720 --> 00:11:56,119
remains a relatively underdeveloped

231
00:11:56,119 --> 00:11:58,279
and under-researched topic,

232
00:11:58,279 --> 00:12:00,360
which is a fascinating one.

233
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:02,120
So with elections coming,

234
00:12:02,120 --> 00:12:05,069
what chances do the pro democratic factions

235
00:12:05,069 --> 00:12:07,809
have against the United Front?

236
00:12:07,809 --> 00:12:10,519
Because of the protests of almost a million

237
00:12:10,519 --> 00:12:14,600
to 2 million people against the extradition
bill,

238
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:17,540
we can safely anticipate that in the upcoming

239
